segments.text: We'd get together, you know, the family, sit and pool our food, and have some, like, you know, invite my brother and friends that would invite Gay Larry, and sometimes they would bring other students.
And when we lived in Red Village, Bert, my brother, was working the mess hall at Duncan Hall.
Oh.
And...
He sometimes would invite us to come and eat there.
And then we took the kids to the band practice.
You know, the band would... Where did it practice in those days?
In the drill field.
Okay.
Did you all go to midnight yell practice?
Uh-huh.
And we were always, like, when the band...

i don't know in the evening they used to march and we hear the band and we had to look for our kids because they would run down you know to come down from that village to on campus to to see the band the uh uh other uh aggie events did you all go to silver taps
We attended Silver Patch.
What was your impression of Silver Patch?
Well, the first time, it was just tremendous.
I mean, I couldn't believe.
Something just came over you.
I cannot describe it.
It's something you cannot describe.
And then did you go to Bonfire?
Oh, yes.
Where was it held?
On the drill field.
And made of logs.
And all kinds of scrap and stuff that they put in.
And let's see, and then we talked about football.
Did y'all ever go walking in an afternoon?
Oh, yes.
Where would you go?
Well, we just went around Vet Village, or if we were in College View, we'd go around, you know, the places.
Right.
Now, Vet Village, where was it?
You know where the President's House is?
Oh, okay.
Just across the street from the stadium.
Okay, that's what I, all right.
And that's what was torn down after your first year?
Yeah.
Okay, that's what I thought.
And was College View new then?
No.
Oh, it was just full?
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
The...
So you didn't meet many people from Bryan.
No.
It was just around the campus.
Around the campus and what we met at church.
All right.
Did you meet any of the campus leaders' wives?
Any of the president's wife or the dean's wife?
No, no.
We didn't.
I did know Odette Smith and Fred Smith.
I don't know whether you ever knew them or not.
Those were the only ones that we knew.
Okay.
Then, let's see.
So you're gone one summer, but then you're back the next summer.
And here, what was a summer in College Station like in terms of comfort?
It was hot.
It was hot, but by then we had two fans we'd put in each bedroom, and we tried to keep cool as best we could.
And everybody was in the same boat.
I mean, we didn't have air conditioning, and we had lots of windows.

and but you know at the time we just knew it was hot we had to just bear and do the best we could what did a hard-working student wife wear what was considered proper dress for her when she was in the apartment working
in the apartment working?
Well, you didn't wear shorts hardly because, well, you know, when we first came here, seldom did you find a woman on campus that first year.

And so when you were in your apartment, out of we had to dress, I mean, we dressed in skirts and blouses because you never knew, very seldom did you see a wife that was very daring that had shorts on, but we went like this, you know.
And then when you went to the store.
Oh, we were dressed.
I mean, we wouldn't dare go to the store in shorts.
Not even in slacks do I remember.
Did you all wear hats to church?
Yes.
I know when we left here in November, my brother and Ralph came and packed everything, and I know Ralph threw away some of my hats.
Now when y'all took things, when you moved things back and forth from Beeville or San Antonio to here, how did you move it?
We had a little trailer.
Oh, okay.
A little trailer.
Okay.
That we moved things in.
Because I thought renting trucks wasn't very easy in those days.
No.
Well, his uncle, no, no, we didn't rent trailers.
Yeah, we rented trailers one time, but his uncle had a pickup, and we used his uncle's pickup.
And during your years here,
you all were able to pay your bills between the GI Bill and what you both earned.
Yes.
And you began to work.
We never got anything on credit.
And you began to work your second year here?
Yes.
So you worked for two years.
Two years.
Two years.
Ralph worked pretty well the... Yeah, from the end, well, about three months of his life.
Sophomore year, and then his junior and senior, and then he worked during the summer for Smith Motor Sales.
Describe how you began to become touched by Aggie spirit.
Aggie feelings?
Well, I did have a lot of feelings as a wife.
But I think when you became an Aggie mom, you had the same spirit.
You wanted to attend everything.
I was in San Antonio, and they had the A&M Club, and we attended some of the functions.
As a former student, Ralph would get letters from the Aggie Moms Club to support their barbecue.

And I think, well, I already had it when my brothers were here, you know, it began to, but I think when Ralph was here, it was, became more prominent in our lives that the Agus period was something that you, was ingrained in you or something, but you cannot describe it.
What builds it?
What contributes to the development of the Holy Spirit?
I think because of the loyalty that's here among the students.
And then it was among the wives that we were all in the same boat.
We all had the same problems.
We had the same joys.
And I think that the band was something that we heard every day because we lived so close.
And then the traditions that were here.
Which traditions?
Well, like the traditions of the bonfire, the traditions of the Yale practice, the traditions of going to football games and standing.
The silver caps?
That was something that you couldn't describe.
That was something that really touched us.
And then the tradition of just being an Aggie, an Aggie wife, it was just something that

Being an Aggie was something that you were proud of, and being the wife of an Aggie, you know, it was... Did any of your friends go through any tragedies that the rest of you helped them, helped support them through while you were students?
Well, the only one, and it really wasn't a tragedy, but, you know, divorce was something that was not dealt with in our family because we, there was, I don't think we had any.
And our neighbor, the Daniels, he was a veterinary student, and they,
Chris would come in every morning and have coffee with me.
Now, they were not veterans.
They came from well-to-do families up in the East, and they were being supported by their family.
And they had three little girls.
And Chris was somebody that she wasn't, I don't know, she just,
wasn't a good, I wouldn't say a good mother because she was, but she was not a very stable person.
And I helped her with the girls.
She'd come in in the morning and have coffee with me and the little girls would be asleep and I would have to tell her, you know, you need to go and feed those little girls.

Well they they went to Fort Worth because he had to go this a mean turn because of his and then all of a sudden his he was back with the two little girls and he was going through a divorce and then we were all subpoenaed to court
And he came, I didn't know how to talk to him because I didn't, he came to tell me that Chris was trying to take the girls away from him.
And he had, she had put them in, she had taken them, when they were in Fort Worth, put them in an orphan home, ran off with another man, and left Roger.
And so when he came, he was just devastated.
And he came to me and wanted me to help
him that he was a good father, that I would probably have to go to court and testify because he had finally found the girls in our room and gotten them out.
And his mother came to stay with him to keep the girls.
And it was such a traumatic thing when you were subpoenaed to court.
Because I liked Chris.
I knew she wasn't stable, but I didn't want to have to stand up.
And I knew what Roger was going through, so that was one of the hardest things that I had to go through when we were here.
It was that.
And did other Aggies help?
Yes, well the one, the Bobby upstairs, that lived upstairs, was subpoenaed to.
Now she was picked up from the back by the sheriff.
I wasn't because he knocked on my door and I looked out the window.
As I, I don't know, one made me look out the window and I saw the sheriff car and the, and I,
He knocked again and again, and finally he said, I said, who is it?
And he says, I'm the sheriff of Brazos County.
Well, I was about to open the door.
And so I said, well, what do you need?
And he said, I need, you know, to give you this dollar.
If you accepted that dollar, then they could put you in the car and take you in.
Oh, okay.
So I said, no, just tell me what I need to do.
So he told me all what I need to do.
And Darnell had a telephone.
So I got on the phone.
I went over to Darnell's, and I think I called Guyon Hall and told Ralph.
And Darnell's husband, he would always study in the afternoon.
And he drove me down to the courthouse.
And I was just listening to everything that was being said, and Bobby was there, and Bobby said they picked me up at the bank because she took the dollar.
But we didn't have to testify.
The lawyer said there was enough or whatever evidence, and the judge awarded the children to Roger.
Now, during that period,
What did students, be they single or married, what were their excesses?
Like did any of your friends in College View, were there many smokers?
Yes.
Helen Darin smoked, chain smoked.
Now she was the only one that smoked.
What about the men?
Were many of them smokers?
No.
I don't remember seeing the men smokers.
And if they smoked, did they smoke cigarettes or pipes?
I believe there was one student in the Red Village that smoked cigars.
Cigars.
But I think his family could afford to.
And was there much beer being drunk?
No.
I never heard of anybody getting drunk or having beer in their home in Bed Village.
Of course, we weren't allowed to.
And Whiskey Bridge had to go west to get whiskey.
But I never heard of any of the people in our little area that would go or drink.
And Ralph said that y'all weren't dancers.
No.
So you didn't go to any of the big A&M dances.
No.
Do you remember any famous celebrities coming to, other than Eisenhower, any of the entertainers, big bands?
I can't remember them.
We came to Gynehall to see them.
What was their name?
Jan Garber?
No.
We saw two of them.
Guy Lombardo?
No.
Oh, what was his name?
I have it in the tip of my tongue and I can't say it.
Were there regular...
Guy and Hall had a... A series of inter... Yeah.
maybe before a football game, and it was usually the Baylor football game, where they would bring a big-name band to give a concert.
And it was just before the Baylor game.
Now let's see, were you all here in the fall of 52?
Yes.
All right, that would have been the election, Adlai Stevenson and Eisenhower.
Yeah.
Do you remember anything happening politically?
No, not much.
Nobody got very much involved or anything?
No.
Most of the veteran students, well, they had to do a lot of studying because some of them had been out of school for so long.
And some of them were taking hard, like,

in college view the lord wallace was a vet student betch was a vet student louis was a vet student roger across the hall was a vet student so they spent all their time all afternoon well they were gone all day till maybe about nine o'clock at night and about how many units apartments were there in each
In Vet Village it was two, you know that.
But in College View?
In College View there was one, two, three, four, eight in one building.
And so that was usually your little community.
Yes.
Now did any of the students study together much?
Well, I don't know, like Roger did his own, the veterinary students did their own studying, you know, by themselves.
I do, because Roger studied by himself.
Bage studied at home.
Wallace and Lewis and they would go to the library, I don't know where they studied, maybe at the, maybe at the,
vet school, because we didn't see them very much.
Did you women ever talk about taking courses in the summer?
No, none of us did.
And we could have.
We could have taken summer courses, but I guess

like when we were at Red Village and Ralph was working, you know, the hours just didn't, I didn't start taking courses until I went back, we went back to San Antonio, then I started on my library of science, working on.
Did y'all ever discuss that women ought to be allowed to enroll at A&M?
No.
We didn't, like we just didn't approve that this was a university.
And I think maybe some of us said, well, why isn't everybody in the Corps, you know?
Okay.
Let's see.
I'm trying to think of other topics that I may have overlooked.
I guess Ralph told you that his end of his sophomore year his grandmother died, and then the fall of 52 my brother was killed in a plane crash.
He had gotten his degree just in May.

because let's see y'all didn't go to to any final review uh and he didn't get any senior boots no uh but he was telling me about how he got his senior ring do you remember anything special they all did when he got his senior ring no i think did he tell you how
My brother paid for it.
Yes, yes, yes.
He put on the check loan.
Oh, is that right?
My brother, the oldest one, graduated in 39, is very, very frugal.
And he says, now, when you all graduate,
I want to give you all your rings."
Well, mine was like $20 and I think Ralph's was $30.
And he sent us a check for $50 and he put on their loan.
He could take it out of his income tax.
But I think when we got the rings, we may have gone out and
And celebrate.
I think that's the only thing we did.
And I don't remember, I think we went to, there were not very many places to go eat.
Yeah, where would you go eat as a special place then?
There was the, you know, the hotel had a restaurant.
I don't remember the name of the hotel.
You mean downtown?
Down in Bryan.
The LaSalle Hotel?
Mm-hmm.
But I know we went someplace, and I can't remember where, that we went to eat.
It may have been a hamburger place, but I remember doing that.
And we didn't go to final reviews.
We did attend final reviews, but Ralph was never involved.
As you look back, what did A&M do best?
For us, well I think A&M gave us the opportunity to get an education, for Ralph to get an education.
And it did, we made a lot of friends here that we kept up through the years.
We got
closer to the spirit of A&M and the traditions.
We experience a closeness.
Even though Ralph was not in the Corps, but the students, we got together.
And I think what A&M really did for us was,
help us with a challenge to try to do better.
And we got that from being close, like Mr. Putty was one of the person that was instrumental and said, you never give up.
Can you think of anything then or now that you wished A&M had done that it didn't do?
Well, at that time,
Well, like when Ralph was looking for a job, I don't think, now my pressure was that I don't think they did enough for him to try to get a job.
And that was, even though we thought it was a great school to get out and everything,
I know he had made a lot of applications, and he would come and say, you know.
And there wasn't any one, any central job placement office, was there?
No, no.
You had to go to each?
Yeah.
And you all never had any financial crises?
No.
We never, like when I had the surgery, one of the members of the Baptist Church here had sold us a little small, I mean a health insurance.
And we weren't paying very much, but we, you know, it was enough.
And so Dr. Lancaster looked at the policy and he says, that's all I'm gonna charge you.
Whatever the policy pays, whatever it pays for, because he owned the hospital, he and Dr. Miller.
And whatever the insurance paid, that's what he got.
Oh, how good, how good.
Now let's see, and he went back to his old job.
Yes, at Smith Boater Sales.
So A&M had no part in that.
No.
And from there he went civil service.
What are the qualities of being an Aggie?
I think really to be a true Aggie, the qualities is being loyal.
To whom?
Being loyal to God, to your country, to the school.
Not thinking of yourself, but of service to others.
And when did you, you got that first, I guess, through your brothers.
Yes.
And then through your husband, but through your own experience here.
In honesty and truthfulness.
Now that has led you, since 1953, to be active in a number of different ways.
When did you become active in the Aggie Mothers Clubs?
Why at that time?
Because of Robert's enrollment at A&M.
Ah, okay.
So you became a fish, Aggie mother.
Yes, and I went on through.
active in the club and I was president of the San Antonio A&M Mothers Club in 1974-75.
Then I applied for an officer in the Federation.
I went through several offices and I was president in 83-84.
and became involved in the Aggie Wives Club.
San Antonio is the only wives club.
And I went through the offices and I served as president at 91, 92 of the Aggie Wives Club.
I was very involved in San Antonio when I became a, well I went to teach at Edgewood, then I became librarian.
at Highlands High School, was there 20 years.
But I also served as president of the San Antonio Business and Professional Women's Club.
So you've been a joiner of many good clubs.
Yeah, we've done, and like the Aggie Moms give scholarships, the Aggie Wives give two scholarships.
One is a core scholarship and one is general.
And it's $1,000 a semester for each one.
And I just, of course I was involved in Lady of the Light too with the scholarship in getting started the women that went back to school.
Yeah, I helped some of them with scholarships for quite a few years.
And so, but I think that came from where we were here at A&M that we helped each other.
You know we were living in Vet Village helping each other, College View we were helping each other.
And like I kept up with Irene Larson, Wallace of course is gone, he's dead, but his son is one of the county commissioners in San Antonio.
And she lives in San Antonio.
As far as you know, are the Aggie Mothers Clubs still progressing?
Oh yes, very much so.
Yes, we have, in fact we're having a federation meeting here, 29th, you know we meet, the federation meets three times a year, in August, January.
in April.
I don't know whether you've ever been to one of our meetings.
In the other years, and if they would ever like me to speak about this project and what I've learned.
Well, I'm going to take your card because the Aggie wives are looking for speakers and the Aggie moms are looking for speakers.
Particularly when they come to the campus, I'd be delighted to chat with them and to share

what the enjoyable information um i i'm always amused when somebody will ask a dumb question you know what in the world are the aggie mothers clubs what do they do and i always tell them that's one group you don't want as your well you know mr chair that's how i met mr cherry uh you know that year they were trying to break the permanent university fund
That's when I first went into the Federation and all my friends told me, just be fourth vice president, just apply for that.
You don't do anything because that's legislation.
You don't do anything.
Well, I did and I got in.
Eleanor Walters from Austin was president and she was the one that encouraged me.
Well, Lord and behold, I get a letter from Mr. Cherry saying that he wants the Mother's Club to help with legislation that the Permanent University Fund was... And I thought, what am I going to do?
And so I called him, and he asked me to come up.
It was in the office that was over in the administration building.
And we talked about it.
